Plot Local Inverse Simpson Index (LISI)

Ramon Massoni-Badosa & Paula Soler-Vila

1 June 2021

1 Introduction

In previous notebooks we have visualized to which extent Harmony was able to correct for batch effects. However, UMAPs represent a 2D visual representation of the data, which is probabilistic, non-linear and largely overplotted. Thus, it is important to quantify the success of the batch effect correction using the latent space (PCA).

To achieve it, we will leverage the Local Inverse Simpson Index (LISI), which measures the batch diversity in the neighborhood of each cell. More precisely, the LISI is the number of cells that can be drawn from a neighbor list before one batch is observed twice. Thus, LISI scores range from 1 to N, where N is the total number of batches in the dataset. We choose LISI over other metrics such as kBET for two main reasons:

  • It is extremely easy to use with a stand-alone package.
  • It is implemented in C++ and scales well to hundreds of thousands of cells.
  • The contribution of each neighbor is weighted.

LISI scores were computed in the previous notebook. Here, we will plot the results.

3 Plot

confounders <- c("library_name", "sex", "age_group", "assay", "hospital")
plot_titles <- c("Library", "Sex", "Age group", "Assay", "Hospital")
lisi_scores$is_integrated <- factor(lisi_scores$is_integrated, levels = c("unintegrated", "integrated"))
lisi_scores_ggs <- purrr::map2(confounders, plot_titles, function(x, title) {
  p <- lisi_scores %>%
    ggplot(aes_string("is_integrated", x, color = "is_integrated")) +
      geom_violin(fill = NA) +
      stat_summary(fun = median, geom = "point", size = 1.25, color= "black") +
      scale_color_manual(values = c("gray60", "limegreen")) +
      labs(title = title, x = "", y = "LISI") +
      theme_classic() +
      theme(
        legend.position = "none",
        plot.title = element_text(size = 13, hjust = 0.5),
        strip.text = element_text(color = "black", size = 12),
        axis.title.x = element_text(color = "black", size = 13),
        axis.text.y = element_text(color = "black", size = 12),
        axis.text.x = element_text(size = 11)
      )
  p
})
names(lisi_scores_ggs) <- confounders
lisi_scores_ggs
